The only production for the start symbol is  
S → NT1 NT6  

Hence the last terminal of any string in the language must be the last terminal produced by NT6.

The possibilities for NT6 are  
• NT6 → 't3'  
• NT6 → 't43'  
• NT6 → 't47'  
• NT6 → NT0 NT4, and NT4 can only be  
  't51', 't8', 't20', 't82', or 't72'.

Thus the last token of any generated string must be one of  
t3, t43, t47, t51, t8, t20, t82, or t72.

The given string ends with t44, which is not in this set.  
Therefore the grammar cannot generate the string.

No

In every derivation that starts from the start-symbol S the final token must come from the non-terminal NT6, because  

 S → NT1 NT6  

Therefore, to decide whether the given sentence can be generated, we only have to look at the possible endings of strings derivable from NT6.

All productions for NT6 are:

 NT6 → NT0 NT4  
 NT6 → 't3' | 't43' | 't47'

If NT6 expands to the single terminals, the last (and only) symbol it contributes is one of {t3, t43, t47}.  
If it expands via NT0 NT4, whatever NT0 produces is followed by whatever NT4 produces, so the last symbol of the whole NT6 string is always what NT4 produces. NT4, however, only yields

 NT4 → 't51' | 't8' | 't20' | 't72' | 't82'

Hence, regardless of the path taken, every string derived from NT6 must end with one of

 t3, t43, t47, t51, t8, t20, t72, t82.

The sentence we were asked to check ends with t42, which is not in this set.  
Consequently no derivation can produce the given string.

No
